{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17629267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17629267"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:04:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:04:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17260"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17260","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17260"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9950"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78055"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9950","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9950"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17260"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63477"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"7646"},{"type":"tags","id":"7651"},{"type":"tags","id":"10695"},{"type":"tags","id":"10718"},{"type":"tags","id":"10719"},{"type":"tags","id":"10721"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23326"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23332"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78055","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78055"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring meiosis, chromosomes undergo several important processes that ensure genetic diversity in gametes. One of these processes was first described by Gregor Mendel through his work with pea plants.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the Law of Independent Assortment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alleles of the same gene separate during meiosis","Dominant alleles always mask recessive alleles","Phenotype ratios always follow 3:1 distribution","Alleles of different genes separate independently during gamete formation","Genes on the same chromosome always inherit together"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Law of Independent Assortment states that\u003Cstrong\u003E alleles of different genes separate independently during gamete formation\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs during metaphase I of meiosis when homologous chromosome pairs align randomly at the metaphase plate, allowing different combinations of maternal and paternal chromosomes to segregate into gametes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDominant alleles always mask recessive alleles\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes complete dominance, which is a pattern of inheritance rather than a law of genetic segregation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlleles of the same gene separate during meiosis\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the Law of Segregation, not Independent Assortment\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenes on the same chromosome always inherit together\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect as crossing over can separate linked genes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhenotype ratios always follow 3:1 distribution\u003C/strong\u003E - This ratio only applies to monohybrid crosses with complete dominance\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIndependent assortment increases genetic diversity by allowing new combinations of alleles to form in gametes. The number of possible combinations increases exponentially with the number of gene pairs being considered.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mendel\u0027s Law of Independent Assortment states that alleles of different genes segregate independently during gamete formation.","Independent assortment occurs during meiosis I when homologous chromosome pairs align randomly at the metaphase plate.","The number of possible gamete combinations is 2^n where n is the number of heterozygous gene pairs."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011","Goldberg ML, Fischer J, Hood L, Hartwell L, Aquadro C. Genetics: From Genes to Genomes. 8th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill Education; 2023."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63477"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17260"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63477"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T11:55:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T11:56:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9950"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78055"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Reme